context: <a2_0>Juscelino Kubitschek<a2_0/>, President of Brazil <b5_0>from <a0_0>1956<a0_0/> to <a1_0>1961<b5_0/><a1_0/>, ordered the construction of <b6_0>Brasília<b6_0/>, fulfilling the promise of the Constitution and his own political campaign promise. Building Brasília was part of Juscelino's <b9_0>"fifty years of prosperity in five" plan<b9_0/>. Lúcio Costa won a contest and was the main urban planner in 1957, with <a3_0><b7_0>5550<b7_0/><a3_0/> people competing. Oscar Niemeyer, a close friend, was the chief architect of most public buildings and Roberto Burle Marx was the landscape designer. Brasília was built in 41 months, from 1956 to <a4_0><b8_0>April 21, 1960<b8_0/><a4_0/>, when it was officially inaugurated.
